cs, law, and social movements to provide a framework for thinking about what we know intuitively: that our society is defined by crisis, risk, and the quest to root out hazards at all costs. Engaging with legal cases, historical examples, and contemporary case studies, Beyond Complicity unfolds the complex role that complicity plays in US law and society today, offering suggestions for how to shift focus away from blame and toward positive, lasting systemic change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAccomplicesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aBlamexSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aConspiracyxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aConspiracyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aResponsibilityxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520394247?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520394247423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520394247/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles